                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>against <persName>Dr Wise's</persName> Heterodoxy—his learning<lb/> I do not fear—nor\n                do I hold back in<lb/> speaking out my mind. How many of our<lb/> Divines do you see\n                fight the Battles of the Lord<lb/> some are afraid that their own character may<lb/>\n                be involved and others are too ignorant<lb/> I know them all—and they know me\n                too<lb/> and therefore as <persName>King David</persName> said<lb/> “<add>תורת\n                    משה</add>”</p>\n            <p>These men can go to public Dinner and<lb/> spout a studied speech upon an old<lb/>\n                hackneyed subject.<lb/> and the public are gulled<lb/> by them because they can\n                flatter and act<lb/> the Sycophant, I do not, and must confess<lb/> you do not, as\n                your Journal proves—<lb/> situated as I am at present I have nothing<lb/> to fear\n                from any of these men—now if<lb/> you consider me worthy your Confidence<lb/> in\n                informing me of the truth—I shall feel<lb/> satisfied so that I may not attach\n                any<lb/> Blame to the innocent—<add>כ\"ד ספרי קודש</add><lb/> this will enable us\n                both to meet in the<lb/> Square and when this matter shall be<lb/> amicably\n                adjusted, I shall be ever ready<lb/> to serve you in writing for your Journal.</p>\n            <p rend=\"The following is written in pencil at the bottom of the page.\">\n                <date>1-10-5615</date>\n            </p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3ws8jc31/canvas/p6"
                }
              ]
            }
